 5.   ^  Alireza Shapur Shahbazi (2005), "The History of the Idea of Iran", in Vesta Curtis ed., Birth of the Persian Empire, IB
      Tauris, London, p. 108: "Similarly the collapse of Sassanian Eranshahr in AD 650 did not end Iranians' national idea. The
      name 'Iran' disappeared from official records of the Saffarids, Samanids, Buyids, Saljuqs and their successor. But one
      unofficially used the name Iran, Eranshahr, and similar national designations, particularly Mamalek-e Iran or "Iranian
      lands", which exactly translated the old Avestan term Ariyanam Daihunam. On the other hand, when the Safavids (not Reza
      Shah, as is popularly assumed) revived a national state officially known as Iran, bureaucratic usage in the Ottoman empire
      and even Iran itself could still refer to it by other descriptive and traditional appellations".
